<title>Exercises</title>

<exercise>
	<title>Rows and columns</title>

	<introduction><p>
		Consider matrix
		<me>
			A = \begin{amatrix}{rrrr}
				 8 \amp -4 \amp -9 \amp -9 \\
				-5 \amp  7 \amp  4 \amp  2 \\
				 6 \amp -8 \amp  1 \amp -5
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
	</p></introduction>

	<task>
		<statement><p> Identify the rows of <m>A</m> as individual row matrices. </p></statement>
		<answer><p>
			The rows of <m>A</m> are:
			<md>
				<mrow> \text{Row 1: } \amp \begin{bmatrix}  8 \amp -4 \amp -9 \amp -9 \end{bmatrix} \text{,} </mrow>
				<mrow> \text{Row 2: } \amp \begin{bmatrix} -5 \amp  7 \amp  4 \amp  2 \end{bmatrix} \text{,} </mrow>
				<mrow> \text{Row 3: } \amp \begin{bmatrix}  6 \amp -8 \amp  1 \amp -5 \end{bmatrix} \text{.} </mrow>
			</md>
		</p></answer>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement><p> Identify the columns of <m>A</m> as individual column matrices. </p></statement>
		<answer><p>
			The columns of <m>A</m> are
			<md>
				<mrow>
					\amp \text{Column 1:} \amp
					\amp \text{Column 2:} \amp
					\amp \text{Column 3:} \amp
					\amp \text{Column 4:}
				</mrow>
				<mrow>
					\amp \begin{amatrix}{r}  8 \\ -5 \\  6 \end{amatrix} \text{,} \amp
					\amp \begin{amatrix}{r} -4 \\  7 \\ -8 \end{amatrix} \text{,} \amp
					\amp \begin{amatrix}{r} -9 \\  4 \\  1 \end{amatrix} \text{,} \amp
					\amp \begin{amatrix}{r} -9 \\  2 \\ -5 \end{amatrix} \text{.}
				</mrow>
			</md>
		</p></answer>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement><p> State the dimensions of <m>A</m>. </p></statement>
		<answer><p> There are three rows and four columns, so the dimensions of <m>A</m> are <m>3 \times 4</m>. </p></answer>
	</task>

</exercise>

<exercise>
	<title>Indexing matrix entries</title>

	<introduction><p>
		Consider matrix
		<me>
			A = \begin{amatrix}{rrrr}
				-2 \amp -1 \amp  5 \\
				 9 \amp -8 \amp  7 \\
				 1 \amp  4 \amp -3 \\
				 3 \amp  6 \amp -5
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
	</p></introduction>

	<task>
		<statement><p> Identify the value of entries <m>a_{12}, a_{33}, a_{41}</m>.</p></statement>
		<answer><p> <m> a_{12} = -1 </m>, <m> a_{33} = -3 </m>, <m> a_{41} = 3 </m>. </p></answer>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement><p> Identify the indices of each of the positive entries of <m>A</m>. </p></statement>
		<answer><p>
			The positive entries are
			<m> a_{13} = 5 </m>,
			<m> a_{21} = 9 </m>,
			<m> a_{23} = 7 </m>,
			<m> a_{31} = 1 </m>,
			<m> a_{32} = 4 </m>,
			<m> a_{41} = 3 </m>,
			<m> a_{42} = 6 </m>.
		</p></answer>
	</task>

</exercise>

<exercise>
	<title>Matrix entries as a function of row and column indices</title>
	<statement><p> Form the <m>4 \times 4</m> matrix <m>A</m> whose entries satisfy the formula <m>a_{ij} = i^2 - j^2</m>. </p></statement>
	<answer><p><m>\displaystyle
		A = \begin{amatrix}{rrrr}
			 0 \amp -3 \amp -8 \amp -15 \\
			 3 \amp  0 \amp -5 \amp -12 \\
			 8 \amp  5 \amp  0 \amp - 7 \\
			15 \amp 12 \amp  7 \amp   0
		\end{amatrix}
	</m></p></answer>
</exercise>

<exercise>
	<title>Restricting matrix entries based on indices</title>
	<statement><p>
		As usual, let <m>i</m> represent the row index and <m>j</m> represent the column index of each entry in a matrix.
		Create a <m>6 \times 6</m> matrix has the following properties:
		<ul>
			<li>
				All entries with <m>i \gt j</m> are zero,
				all other entries are nonzero.
			</li>
			<li> Each nonzero entry is positive if <m>i + j</m> is even and negative if <m>i + j</m> is odd. </li>
			<li> No two nonzero entries have the same absolute value. </li>
		</ul>
	</p></statement>
	<answer><p>
		Here is one possible matrix that satisfies the stated restrictions:
		<me>
			\begin{amatrix}{rrrrrr}
				1 \amp -2 \amp  3 \amp - 4 \amp   5 \amp - 6 \\
				0 \amp  7 \amp -8 \amp   9 \amp -10 \amp  11 \\
				0 \amp  0 \amp 12 \amp -13 \amp  14 \amp -15 \\
				0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  16 \amp -17 \amp  18 \\
				0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp   0 \amp  19 \amp -20 \\
				0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp   0 \amp   0 \amp  21
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
	</p></answer>
</exercise>

<exercise>
	<title>Matrix inequality</title>

	<introduction><p>
		For each example matrix <m>X</m> below,
		give at least one reason why <m>X</m> is not equal to matrix
		<me>
			A = \begin{amatrix}{rrr}
				1 \amp  1 \amp  8 \\
				0 \amp -1 \amp -7
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
	</p></introduction>

	<task>
		<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
			X = \begin{amatrix}{rrrr}
				1 \amp  1 \amp  8 \amp 0 \\
				0 \amp -1 \amp -7 \amp 0
			\end{amatrix}
		</m></p></statement>
		<answer><p> Matrix <m>X</m> is not equal to matrix <m>A</m> because <m>X</m> has a fourth column that <m>A</m> lacks. </p>
		</answer>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
			X = \begin{amatrix}{rrr}
				1 \amp  1 \amp  8 \\
				0 \amp -1 \amp -7 \\
				0 \amp  0 \amp  0
			\end{amatrix}
		</m></p></statement>
		<answer><p> Matrix <m>X</m> is not equal to matrix <m>A</m> because <m>X</m> has a third row that <m>A</m> lacks. </p>
		</answer>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
			X = \begin{amatrix}{rrr}
				1 \amp  1 \amp  8 \\
				0 \amp  1 \amp -7
			\end{amatrix}
		</m></p></statement>
		<answer><p> Matrix <m>X</m> is not equal to matrix <m>A</m> because <m>x_{21} = 1</m> while <m>a_{21} = -1</m>. </p>
		</answer>
	</task>

</exercise>

